  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And Solomon had horses brought out of Egypt",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] R.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "And the horses which Solomon had were brought out of Egypt",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Egypt is an agricultural not a pastoral country; it lacks the broad plains suitable for the rearing of large numbers of horses. Egypt was therefore probably only the market; the raising ground was elsewhere.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and linen yarn: the king’s merchants received the linen yarn at a price",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] R.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "the king’s merchants received them in droves, each drove at a price",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". “Linen yarn” is a mistranslation of a word which perhaps means “drove.” The whole verse refers to traffic in horses. According to a third view the Heb. “miḳvê” means neither “yarn” nor “drove,” but conceals a proper name, known to us from Assyrian inscriptions, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ku‘i",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Kuë",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (= Cilicia). In this case the horses would be brought in the first place from eastern Asia Minor and Armenia, since Cilicia itself is not a horse-breeding country. We then translate, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And the horses which Solomon had were brought out of Egypt and out of Cilicia; the king’s merchants received them from Cilicia at a price",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The further supposition that “Egypt” (Mizraim) is a mistake for “Musri” (a land supposed to lie N.E. of Cilicia) may be true but is difficult to prove.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 16.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Horses brought.., out of Egypt.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Later on we read that horses were imported from other countries as well (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 9:24, 28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), as, for instance, from Arabia and Armenia (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 27:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Linen yarn",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The words are without doubt wrong here. But it is impossible to say with any certainty what should be in their place. The Vulgate shows here ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "from Coa",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", presumably meaning Tekoa, a small place on the road from Egypt to Jerusalem. It might not have been easy to surmise, however, so much as this, but for the fact that the Septuagint shows in the parallel place, \"And from Tekoa\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 1:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The Septuagint, however, has for the present place, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "Καὶ ἡ τιμὴ τῶν ἐμπόρωντοῦ βασίλεως πορεύεσθαι καὶ ἠγόραζον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The Hebrew word here translated \"linen yarn\" is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "מִקְואֵ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (i.q. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "מִקְוֶה",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " niph. of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "קָוָה",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"to be gathered together\").' Gesenius, followed by De Wette (and others), and himself following Piscator (born tire. 1480) and Vatablus (born ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "circ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". 1546), would translate the word \"company,\" and read, \"a company of the king's merchants took a company (of horses) at a price.\" Others would translate the word \"import;\" and read, \"the import of the king's merchants was an import at a price,\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in money. Neither of these renderings can be considered really satisfactory. Some slight corruption of text still baulks us, therefore. 2 Chronicles 1:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
